    • map

      public <T extends Type> T map(Function<TypeConcrete,TypeConcrete> mapper)
      Description copied from interface: TypeConcrete
      Applies a mapper function over this Type and its child Types, if any. Notably this method does not walk the entire Type tree. Specifically, TypeClass will not apply the mapper to its corresponding TypeDeclaration and TypeParameter will not apply the mapper to its corresponding bound. This is to prevent infinite recursion, and to keep instances of TypeParameter the same.
      Specified by:
      map in interface TypeConcrete
      Type Parameters:
      T - The return Type. This may cause a ClassCastException if the mapper does not produce a type of T for the highest level Type
      Parameters:
      mapper - The mapper function to apply
      Returns:
      A (possibly new) Type constructed by mapping this Type and its child Types

    • flatten

      public TypeConcrete flatten()
      Description copied from interface: TypeConcrete
      Flattens this TypeConcrete, simplifying its structure. For example, any TypeAnd with a single element will be reduced to just that element. This may be necessary for checking type equality.
      Specified by:
      flatten in interface TypeConcrete
      Returns:

    • equalsExactly

      public boolean equalsExactly(TypeConcrete o)
      Description copied from interface: TypeConcrete
      Checks if this TypeConcrete is exactly equal to another TypeConcrete. This requires the same type structure, whereas the normal Object.equals(Object) method on TypeConcretes checks for type equality (e.g., a TypeAnd with one element is considered equal to any type which is equal to that element).
      Specified by:
      equalsExactly in interface TypeConcrete
      Parameters:
      o - The other TypeConcrete to check equality against
      Returns:
      True if the this is exactly structurally equal to other
